# framer-motion Best Practices

This document outlines essential best practices for using framer-motion in React applications. By following these guidelines, you'll ensure that your animations are performant, accessible, and maintainable.

## Code Organization and Structure

### Use Consistent Imports

Always import from `motion/react` to ensure you're using the latest version of the library.

```javascript
❌ BAD
import { motion } from "framer-motion";

✅ GOOD
import { motion, AnimatePresence } from "motion/react";
```

### Component Structure

Organize your components to separate animation logic from business logic. This keeps your code clean and easier to maintain.

```javascript
// AnimationComponent.js
import { motion } from "motion/react";

const AnimationComponent = ({ isVisible }) => (
  <motion.div
    initial={{ opacity: 0 }}
    animate={{ opacity: 1 }}
    exit={{ opacity: 0 }}
  />
);

// ParentComponent.js
import AnimationComponent from './AnimationComponent';

const ParentComponent = ({ isVisible }) => (
  <AnimationComponent isVisible={isVisible} />
);
```

## Common Patterns and Anti-patterns

### Use AnimatePresence for Conditional Rendering

Always wrap components that should animate on mount/unmount with `AnimatePresence`.

```javascript
❌ BAD
const Item = ({ isVisible }) => (
  {isVisible && <motion.div>Content</motion.div>}
);

✅ GOOD
const Item = ({ isVisible }) => (
  <AnimatePresence>
    {isVisible && (
      <motion.div
        initial={{ opacity: 0 }}
        animate={{ opacity: 1 }}
        exit={{ opacity: 0 }}
      />
    )}
  </AnimatePresence>
);
```

### Layout Changes with LayoutGroup

When animating layout changes, use the `layout` prop and wrap with `LayoutGroup` to prevent performance issues.

```javascript
import { motion, LayoutGroup } from "motion/react";

const List = ({ items }) => (
  <LayoutGroup>
    {items.map(item => (
      <motion.div key={item.id} layout>
        {item.content}
      </motion.div>
    ))}
  </LayoutGroup>
);
```

## Performance Considerations

### Animate Only Transform and Opacity

Limit your animations to `transform` and `opacity` properties to keep animations on the GPU.

```javascript
❌ BAD
<motion.div animate={{ width: '100%' }} />

✅ GOOD
<motion.div animate={{ scale: 1 }} />
```

### Avoid Inline Styles

Avoid using inline styles as they can lead to unnecessary re-renders. Use CSS classes or styled-components instead.

```javascript
❌ BAD
<motion.div style={{ margin: '20px' }} />

✅ GOOD
<motion.div className="my-class" />
```

## Common Pitfalls and Gotchas

### Respect User Preferences

Use the `useReducedMotion` hook to respect users' accessibility settings.

```javascript
import { useReducedMotion } from "motion/react";

const MyComponent = () => {
  const shouldReduceMotion = useReducedMotion();
  
  return (
    <motion.div
      animate={shouldReduceMotion ? { opacity: 1 } : { scale: 1 }}
    />
  );
};
```

### Ensure Stable Keys

When using `AnimatePresence`, make sure the direct children have stable keys to avoid unexpected behavior.

```javascript
const ItemList = ({ items }) => (
  <AnimatePresence>
    {items.map(item => (
      <motion.div key={item.id} exit={{ opacity: 0 }}>
        {item.content}
      </motion.div>
    ))}
  </AnimatePresence>
);
```

## Component Architecture

### Use Functional Components

Always prefer functional components with hooks over class components for better performance and cleaner code.

```javascript
❌ BAD
class MyComponent extends React.Component {
  render() {
    return <motion.div>Content</motion.div>;
  }
}

✅ GOOD
const MyComponent = () => <motion.div>Content</motion.div>;
```

## State Management

### Local State with useState

Use the `useState` hook for local component state management when controlling animations.

```javascript
import { useState } from "react";

const ToggleItem = () => {
  const [isVisible, setIsVisible] = useState(false);

  return (
    <>
      <button onClick={() => setIsVisible(!isVisible)}>Toggle</button>
      <Item isVisible={isVisible} />
    </>
  );
};
```

## Accessibility

### Ensure Focus Management

When animating elements that affect focus, ensure that focus is managed properly to enhance accessibility.

```javascript
const FocusableItem = () => {
  const ref = useRef(null);

  const handleClick = () => {
    ref.current.focus();
  };

  return (
    <motion.div onClick={handleClick} ref={ref} tabIndex={0}>
      Click Me
    </motion.div>
  );
};
```

## Hooks Best Practices

### Custom Hooks for Animation Logic

Encapsulate complex animation logic in custom hooks to keep your components clean and focused.

```javascript
import { useAnimation } from "motion/react";

const useFadeIn = (duration = 0.5) => {
  const controls = useAnimation();

  const fadeIn = () => {
    controls.start({ opacity: 1, transition: { duration } });
  };

  const fadeOut = () => {
    controls.start({ opacity: 0, transition: { duration } });
  };

  return { controls, fadeIn, fadeOut };
};

// Usage
const MyComponent = () => {
  const { controls, fadeIn } = useFadeIn();

  useEffect(() => {
    fadeIn();
  }, []);

  return <motion.div animate={controls}>Content</motion.div>;
};
```

By adhering to these guidelines, you'll create animations that are not only visually appealing but also performant and accessible. Happy coding!